The VF is primarily focused on display and structure and therefore [has minimal JS](https://visual-framework.github.io/vf-welcome/developing/guidelines/javascript/). This also helps if you‚Äôd like to use, say, Bootstrap for tab behaviour but use the VF look.

Similar to our CSS approach, the VF JS never targets HTML elements or even CSS classes and instead uses [JS data attributes](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/HTML/Howto/Use_data_attributes#JavaScript_access); for example a partial look at [`vf-tabs`](https://visual-framework.github.io/vf-core/components/detail/vf-tabs.html):

```html
<div class="vf-tabs-content" data-vf-js-tabs-content>
    <section class="vf-tabs__section" id="vf-tabs__section--1">
        <h2>Section 1</h2>
```
The Visual Framework uses `class="vf-tabs-content"` for the visual styling and `data-vf-js-tabs-content` for the JS ‚Äî exclusively. Use the VF JS where it‚Äôs helpful, if you don‚Äôt need it, don‚Äôt add the `data-*` and use your own JS.

With that in mind, we‚Äôll carry on and focus on the CSS. 

